</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,958,564,630]" box="[264,958,564,630]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis box="[264,389,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Etymology</emphasis>
Named for the paradise-like beauty of the 
<typeStatus box="[807,857,604,630]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,816,684,750]" box="[264,816,684,750]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis box="[264,407,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Distribution</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[312,455,724,750]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">VANUATU</collectingCountry>
: Santo, Millennium Cave area.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,1322,804,1390]" box="[264,387,804,829]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
<emphasis box="[264,387,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Comments</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,1322,804,1390]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Known so far only from the Millennium Cave area (Sarakata River watershed) on Santo, the larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[501,664,884,909]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradisium">
<emphasis box="[501,664,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S. paradisium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are habitat specialists of fast, shallow water. They were taken in moderately large numbers from smooth travertine substrate in fast flow (
<quantity box="[1218,1289,924,950]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" unit="m" value="1.5">1.5 m</quantity>
/s), along with low numbers of larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[724,914,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="steatopygium">
<emphasis box="[724,914,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S. steatopygium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[978,1150,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="callipygium">
<emphasis box="[978,1150,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S. callipygium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Larvae show steatopygous modification to the abdomen in addition to possessing, by far, the largest number of hooks comprising the posterior circlet of any 
<collectingCountry box="[1001,1097,1044,1070]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
simuliid — both structural attributes known as adaptations to fast-flowing water (
<bibRefCitation author="Palmer, R. W. &amp; Craig, D. A." box="[1035,1317,1084,1110]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="199 - 218" refId="ref42368" refString="Palmer, R. W. &amp; Craig, D. A. (2000) An ecological classification of primary labral fans of filterfeeding black fly (Diptera: Simuliidae) larvae. Canadian Journal of Zoology, 78, 199 - 218." type="journal article" year="2000">Palmer and Craig 2000</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Craig, D. A." box="[264,399,1124,1150]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="1079 - 1093" refId="ref41359" refString="Craig, D. A. (2003) Geomorphology, development of running water habitats, and evolution of black flies on Polynesian islands. BioScience, 53, 1079 - 1093." type="journal article" year="2003">Craig 2003</bibRefCitation>
). Larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[539,701,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradisium">
<emphasis box="[539,701,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S. paradisium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
notably do not twist the body to place the labral fans into the mainstream flow –– again, a known adaptation to thin films of fast water (Crosskey 1990, 
<bibRefCitation author="Craig, D. A." box="[463,599,1204,1230]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" pagination="855 - 904" refId="ref41323" refString="Craig, D. A. (1997) A taxonomic revision of the Pacific black fly subgenus Inseliellum (Diptera: Simuliidae). Canadian Journal of Zoology, 75, 855 - 904." type="journal article" year="1997">Craig 1997</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="64.[264,1322,804,1390]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">
Of all the 
<collectingCountry box="[428,524,1244,1270]" name="Vanuatu" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Vanuatu</collectingCountry>
simuliids, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craig &amp; Currie &amp; Hunter &amp; Spironello" authorityYear="2006" box="[652,814,1244,1269]" class="Insecta" family="Simuliidae" genus="Simulium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="64" pageNumber="65" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradisium">
<emphasis box="[652,814,1244,1269]" italics="true" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">S. paradisium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has perhaps the most colourful larvae, with multiple colours of the head spots set off against a dark brown background and with a pale body. The spectacular colouration of the larva seems appropriate, given the stunning beauty of its 
<typeStatus box="[416,466,1364,1390]" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">type</typeStatus>
locality, a true jungle paradise (
<figureCitation box="[842,945,1364,1390]" captionStart="FIGURE 24" captionStartId="83.[264,367,1634,1658]" captionTargetBox="[301,1278,310,1610]" captionTargetId="figure-141@83.[301,1279,310,1610]" captionTargetPageId="83" captionText="FIGURE 24. Habitats of larvae of Hebridosimulium species. a–e. Vanuatu.a. Santo, Adsone River. Type locality of S. adsonense. b. Santo, upper cascade, tributary of Sarakata River. Type locality of S. paradisium. c. Efate, Mele Cascade. Type locality of S. steatopygium. Note travertine terraces. d. South Pentecost, Warbot River. Type locality of S. supercilium. e. Santo, small stream, Millennium Cave region. Typical locality of S. subparadisium. f–i. Fiji. Habitats of S. laciniatum larvae. f. Viti Levu, Abaca Village, above Vereni Falls. Type region. g. Taveuni, Wairiki, Devo Peak, looking down water slide. h. Kadavu, Kadavacoro Village, Wailea Waterfall. i. Vanu Levu, Waisala Rain Forest Reserve, Ravini River." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5071449" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5071449/files/figure.png" pageId="64" pageNumber="65">Fig. 24b</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
